00:20:53,170 --> 00:20:56,040
This can also be helpful if
you're looking for weird cases.

489
00:20:56,040 --> 00:20:57,740
If, for example,
in the screen size,

490
00:20:57,740 --> 00:21:01,238
we saw only one observation way
out here, like 100 something,

491
00:21:01,238 --> 00:21:02,780
well, then we know
that it's probably

492
00:21:02,780 --> 00:21:04,550
just an error in
the data collection

493
00:21:04,550 --> 00:21:07,070
and we should drop
that observation.

494
00:21:07,070 --> 00:21:10,930
But from first glance,
this looks good.

495
00:21:10,930 --> 00:21:12,980
So now we can get on
to the analyze step,

496
00:21:12,980 --> 00:21:14,740
and that's done by
fitting a model,

497
00:21:14,740 --> 00:21:17,600
by building the model
in their verbiage.

498
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:19,640
And you have two
options to go with.

499
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:22,100
You have standard build
and you have quick build.

500
00:21:22,100 --> 00:21:26,620
Standard build, you can see
takes between two to four hours.

501
00:21:26,620 --> 00:21:28,750
The reason this takes so
long is because there's

502
00:21:28,750 --> 00:21:30,550
a lot of different
machine learning

503
00:21:30,550 --> 00:21:32,210
models we could choose from.

504
00:21:32,210 --> 00:21:35,860
And since we're trying to
let the computer, the Amazons

505
00:21:35,860 --> 00:21:38,890
models, automatically
determine the correct model

506
00:21:38,890 --> 00:21:42,190
to fit to this data,
you have this outcome

507
00:21:42,190 --> 00:21:45,820
or this effect where
they have to try

508
00:21:45,820 --> 00:21:47,240
so many different combinations.

509
00:21:47,240 --> 00:21:49,120
And if I say I'm willing
to wait two to four hours,

510
00:21:49,120 --> 00:21:51,203
then they're going to try
every single combination

511
00:21:51,203 --> 00:21:53,870
to see if they can get that last
little bit of performance out.

512
00:21:53,870 --> 00:21:57,270
Now, the actual
change in performance

513
00:21:57,270 --> 00:21:59,940
might be so minuscule
between the first model

514
00:21:59,940 --> 00:22:02,970
they try and the model
after four hours,

515
00:22:02,970 --> 00:22:06,180
and so we might actually not get
a huge magnitude in improvement.

516
00:22:06,180 --> 00:22:07,710
But it might show
some improvement,

517
00:22:07,710 --> 00:22:10,490
and therefore, they'll
take that as a win.

518
00:22:10,490 --> 00:22:12,990
I would argue as again, from a
statistician's point of view,

519
00:22:12,990 --> 00:22:15,363
it's not very appropriate
to worry about that.

520
00:22:15,363 --> 00:22:17,280
We should take a much
more principled approach

521
00:22:17,280 --> 00:22:19,210
and try things that
make sense for our data.

522
00:22:19,210 --> 00:22:20,890
But again, not a
statistics class.

523
00:22:20,890 --> 00:22:23,590
We're just treating this as a
magic black box for a second.

524
00:22:23,590 --> 00:22:26,130
And so we can go this route and
choose either standard build

525
00:22:26,130 --> 00:22:28,110
or quick build,
which says, OK, let's

526
00:22:28,110 --> 00:22:29,910
not fit as many
different combinations.

527
00:22:29,910 --> 00:22:32,020
Let's just try a few models.

528
00:22:32,020 --> 00:22:33,418
Takes 2 to 15 minutes.

529
00:22:33,418 --> 00:22:35,460
I would argue again, for
a data set of this size,

530
00:22:35,460 --> 00:22:38,070
it should be taking on
the order of milliseconds.

531
00:22:38,070 --> 00:22:39,460
We'll ignore that for now.

532
00:22:39,460 --> 00:22:43,460
We'll take quick build, and then
you can just click Quick Build.

533
00:22:43,460 --> 00:22:46,850
Now, I've already run this,
but I'll click it there.

534
00:22:46,850 --> 00:22:48,890
And you can see it-- when
it comes up with this,

535
00:22:48,890 --> 00:22:51,110
you can just click
Start Quick Build,

536
00:22:51,110 --> 00:22:52,440
and then it'll start training.

537
00:22:52,440 --> 00:22:54,480
And again, it'll take
between 2 to 15 minutes.

538
00:22:54,480 --> 00:22:56,120
There's some variability in it.

539
00:22:56,120 --> 00:22:57,890
But I've already
trained one now,

540
00:22:57,890 --> 00:23:00,210
so you can click
that, lectures run.

541
00:23:00,210 --> 00:23:03,290
But now I'll go on to what
my trained model already

542
00:23:03,290 --> 00:23:04,580
looks like.

543
00:23:04,580 --> 00:23:08,330
So let's go back for a
second to models now.

544
00:23:08,330 --> 00:23:10,580
And if I click
this one here, this

545
00:23:10,580 --> 00:23:12,960
is the one I randomly
created, same data set,

546
00:23:12,960 --> 00:23:16,430
you can see that once
it was fully trained,

547
00:23:16,430 --> 00:23:20,210
it was able to predict the
actual number of shipping days

548
00:23:20,210 --> 00:23:24,440
within a range plus
or minus of 1.22 days.

549
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:25,830
Now, that's not terrible.

550
00:23:25,830 --> 00:23:28,040
If we see here, the range
of days of deliveries

551
00:23:28,040 --> 00:23:30,877
were somewhere between--

552
00:23:30,877 --> 00:23:32,210
forget what exactly what it was.

553
00:23:32,210 --> 00:23:35,670
I think on the low end was 0 and
the high end was 28 or 26 days.

554
00:23:35,670 --> 00:23:40,190
So being off by about a
day or so is pretty good.

555
00:23:40,190 --> 00:23:43,590
Now, the first thing
we see here on the top

556
00:23:43,590 --> 00:23:46,900
is a feature importance,
a variable importance.

557
00:23:46,900 --> 00:23:48,540
So this tells us
which variables were

558
00:23:48,540 --> 00:23:53,040
most important in the prediction
of the actual number of shipping

559
00:23:53,040 --> 00:23:53,880
days.

560
00:23:53,880 --> 00:23:56,190
Now, the first one is
the expected number

561
00:23:56,190 --> 00:23:57,722
of shipping days.

562
00:23:57,722 --> 00:23:59,430
Now, not knowing much
about the data set,

563
00:23:59,430 --> 00:24:01,847
I'd argue that this is probably
not something I would have

564
00:24:01,847 --> 00:24:05,160
included in training the
model, because that's maybe

565
00:24:05,160 --> 00:24:07,290
using some other machine
learning maybe to predict,

566
00:24:07,290 --> 00:24:10,270
expect how many number
of days it takes.

567
00:24:10,270 --> 00:24:12,690
And so once we a good
or if we have a model

568
00:24:12,690 --> 00:24:14,910
that creates a good number
of expected shipping days

569
00:24:14,910 --> 00:24:16,380
and we know that,
well, then it's

570
00:24:16,380 --> 00:24:19,770
not surprising that the actual
shipping days relies mostly

571
00:24:19,770 --> 00:24:20,290
on that.

572
00:24:20,290 --> 00:24:23,980
So arguably a more interesting
model would be to exclude that.

573
00:24:23,980 --> 00:24:27,828
So maybe we'll go back
here and while this

574
00:24:27,828 --> 00:24:29,370
is-- while we're
looking at this one,

575
00:24:29,370 --> 00:24:31,950
we'll train a different
model where we drop off

576
00:24:31,950 --> 00:24:35,110
the expected shipping days.

577
00:24:35,110 --> 00:24:38,800
So let's do this, and I'll just
do Start Quick Build while we

578
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:41,410
look at our other model.

579
00:24:41,410 --> 00:24:43,480
But either way,
going back to this,

580
00:24:43,480 --> 00:24:46,210
we'll see now that we have on
time deliveries, the next most

581
00:24:46,210 --> 00:24:49,270
important, and you can see
the relationship as far

582
00:24:49,270 --> 00:24:53,920
as if it's status
is late, how far off

583
00:24:53,920 --> 00:24:55,390
or how does that affect it?

584
00:24:55,390 --> 00:24:56,922
On time, how does
that affect it?

585
00:24:56,922 --> 00:24:58,630
Again, this is another
thing that maybe I

586
00:24:58,630 --> 00:25:00,922
should exclude from the model
because this is something

587
00:25:00,922 --> 00:25:03,340
I would have to
know on the outcome

588
00:25:03,340 --> 00:25:05,530
or it'd have to occur
before I can know

589
00:25:05,530 --> 00:25:08,230
what the expected shipping days
or the predicted shipping days

590
00:25:08,230 --> 00:25:08,730
are.

591
00:25:08,730 --> 00:25:10,970
So I arguably should
drop this one as well.

592
00:25:10,970 --> 00:25:13,000
So it's really coming
down to shipping priority

593
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,580
in some of these later things.

594
00:25:15,580 --> 00:25:16,420
So yeah.

595
00:25:16,420 --> 00:25:18,200
Either way, irrelevant for this.

596
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:20,090
We're just trying to
see how this tool works.

597
00:25:20,090 --> 00:25:22,780
And you can see now the impact
on the prediction associated

598
00:25:22,780 --> 00:25:24,370
with these different categories.

599
00:25:24,370 --> 00:25:25,150
Cool stuff.

600
00:25:25,150 --> 00:25:26,000
Fun plots.

601
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:27,920
We're good to go.

602
00:25:27,920 --> 00:25:30,830
If we click on Scoring,
you can see here this plot

603
00:25:30,830 --> 00:25:33,050
shows my predicted value
for actual shipping

604
00:25:33,050 --> 00:25:36,860
days versus the actual value
for actual shipping days.

605
00:25:36,860 --> 00:25:40,940
And a good prediction should
result in a really tight line

606
00:25:40,940 --> 00:25:42,975
here, a really tight
fit between these.

607
00:25:42,975 --> 00:25:44,600
A perfect prediction
would be every dot

608
00:25:44,600 --> 00:25:46,260
falls perfectly on the line.

609
00:25:46,260 --> 00:25:48,110
But for the most
part here, we're

610
00:25:48,110 --> 00:25:49,920
decently close to this line.

611
00:25:49,920 --> 00:25:51,800
There's a pretty
strong relationship,

612
00:25:51,800 --> 00:25:54,527
so I feel pretty
good about that.

613
00:25:54,527 --> 00:25:56,360
If I click on that
advanced metrics as well,

614
00:25:56,360 --> 00:25:59,360
you can see also the
distribution of errors,

615
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:01,620
and we do see that they're
kind of nice, symmetrical.

616
00:26:01,620 --> 00:26:05,150
So for the most part, the
range of typical error

617
00:26:05,150 --> 00:26:09,150
is falling between
0.71 and negative 0.71.

618
00:26:09,150 --> 00:26:11,960
So again, a decent result.

619
00:26:11,960 --> 00:26:14,880
Root mean squared error
of 1.22, as we saw before.

620
00:26:14,880 --> 00:26:18,300
And if you're familiar with R
squared, you're getting 87.5.

621
00:26:18,300 --> 00:26:20,660
That's basically
saying, the percentage

622
00:26:20,660 --> 00:26:24,980
of variance explained by
this model is about 87.5%.

623
00:26:24,980 --> 00:26:26,520
Again, not a statistic class.

624
00:26:26,520 --> 00:26:28,320
I don't expect you to
have-- to understand

625
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:30,180
exactly why that worked.

626
00:26:30,180 --> 00:26:32,190
But once we have
that, conceivably now,

627
00:26:32,190 --> 00:26:34,645
we could predict
this onto new data.

628
00:26:34,645 --> 00:26:36,270
We don't really have
any new data sets,

629
00:26:36,270 --> 00:26:39,213
so we'll just make a prediction
onto our existing data.

630
00:26:39,213 --> 00:26:40,630
But we'll see how
to do that here.

631
00:26:40,630 --> 00:26:42,370
So we're doing a
Batch Prediction.

632
00:26:42,370 --> 00:26:44,010
We'll click our
consolidated shipping

633
00:26:44,010 --> 00:26:47,490
data, Generate Predictions.

634
00:26:47,490 --> 00:26:49,167
And then it'll take
a few seconds here,

635
00:26:49,167 --> 00:26:51,000
but then this will make
predictions for each

636
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:53,603
of our 10,000 observations.

637
00:26:53,603 --> 00:26:55,770
But again, the important
thing here would be to do--

638
00:26:55,770 --> 00:26:57,900
assuming we have a
different set, a test set,

639
00:26:57,900 --> 00:27:00,900
if you want to say, that would
allow us to make our predictions

640
00:27:00,900 --> 00:27:04,340
onto a new data set.

641
00:27:04,340 --> 00:27:08,720
And if we preview these,
this is our predicted number

642
00:27:08,720 --> 00:27:11,180
of shipping days and the
actual number of shipping days.

643
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:12,770
Predicted, actual.

644
00:27:12,770 --> 00:27:14,350
Predicted, actual.

645
00:27:14,350 --> 00:27:16,680
So again, you can see
really good results here.

646
00:27:16,680 --> 00:27:19,370
But again, arguably we leaked a
little bit too much information

647
00:27:19,370 --> 00:27:21,440
in here for this.

648
00:27:21,440 --> 00:27:26,900
Either way though, that is the
process of training this model.

649
00:27:26,900 --> 00:27:29,570
Once we've done that, we can
go back here-- and actually,

650
00:27:29,570 --> 00:27:31,140
let's see if our model
finished our other one.

651
00:27:31,140 --> 00:27:31,220
Yeah.

652
00:27:31,220 --> 00:27:32,730
So this other one
finished training.

653
00:27:32,730 --> 00:27:35,160
You can see that the
performance was worse.

654
00:27:35,160 --> 00:27:37,380
Now we're back down to 1.55.

655
00:27:37,380 --> 00:27:40,250
And I'd argue, if you drop
shipping priority and arguably

656
00:27:40,250 --> 00:27:43,550
on time delivery, you'd
get even worse results.

657
00:27:43,550 --> 00:27:47,870
Though the worse here is just
in this numeric value because

658
00:27:47,870 --> 00:27:49,580
in practice, we
could use a model

659
00:27:49,580 --> 00:27:54,473
that didn't include
on time delivery--

660
00:27:54,473 --> 00:27:56,390
actually, shipping
priority, we could include.

661
00:27:56,390 --> 00:27:57,848
But yeah, model
that didn't include

662
00:27:57,848 --> 00:28:00,020
on time delivery
or arguably date,

663
00:28:00,020 --> 00:28:02,300
while it would have
worse performance,

664
00:28:02,300 --> 00:28:05,490
it would actually be usable
in practice on a new data

665
00:28:05,490 --> 00:28:07,150
set that we haven't seen before.

666
00:28:07,150 --> 00:28:10,268
So that would be a good outcome.

667
00:28:10,268 --> 00:28:12,310
But either way, yeah, once
you're done with this,

668
00:28:12,310 --> 00:28:14,350
you can just come in here and
delete these models really

669
00:28:14,350 --> 00:28:14,870
easily.

670
00:28:14,870 --> 00:28:17,760
Just click on the little
radio buttons, Delete.

671
00:28:17,760 --> 00:28:19,750
Delete.

